# Agile Framework for AI Agent Development

## Core Principles

1. Release Planning First
   - All user stories are created during the release planning phase
   - Stories map directly to release plan requirements from docs/technical/RELEASE_PLAN.md
   - No new stories are created during sprints
   - Stories are estimated and prioritized before sprint planning

2. Release Plan Source of Truth
   - Release plan is maintained in docs/technical/RELEASE_PLAN.md
   - All user stories must map to release plan requirements
   - Release plan changes trigger user story review
   - Sprint planning references release plan directly

3. Architectural Continuity and Code Reuse [CRITICAL]
   - Each sprint builds upon previous sprint's codebase
   - Architecture decisions consider full release plan vision
   - Code reuse is prioritized over new implementations
   - Technical debt is addressed proactively
   - Common functionality is abstracted for reuse
   - Documentation tracks architectural decisions
   - Changes maintain backward compatibility
   - New features extend existing architecture
   - Regular architecture reviews ensure alignment
   - Cross-sprint dependencies are identified early

4. User Story Creation
   - Created during release planning phase
   - Must map to specific release plan requirements
   - Includes full acceptance criteria and test cases
   - Technical dependencies identified upfront

## Release Planning Process

1. Requirements Analysis
   - Review release plan from docs/technical/RELEASE_PLAN.md
   - Identify core features and dependencies
   - Map technical architecture needs
   - Define success criteria

2. User Story Creation
   - Create stories for each requirement
   - Define acceptance criteria
   - Write test cases
   - Document technical approach

3. Story Refinement
   - Review and refine stories
   - Identify dependencies
   - Estimate complexity
   - Prioritize based on value

4. Release Backlog Creation
   - Organize stories by feature area
   - Define story relationships
   - Set target milestones
   - Plan testing strategy

## Sprint Planning Process

1. Story Selection
   - Select from existing release backlog
   - No new story creation
   - Consider team capacity
   - Maintain feature dependencies

2. Sprint Backlog
   - Subset of release backlog
   - Stories are "ready" state
   - Clear acceptance criteria
   - Defined test cases

3. Sprint Execution
   - Implement selected stories
   - Follow test-first approach
   - Regular progress updates
   - No scope changes

## User Story Template

```markdown
# US-[Area][Number]: As a [role] I want [capability]

As a [role]
I want [capability]
So that [benefit]

## Business Value
[Clear statement of value delivered]

## Acceptance Criteria
Each criterion should be:
- Testable: Can be verified through automated tests
- Specific: Clear and unambiguous
- Independent: Can be tested in isolation
- Relevant: Directly related to user value

Format:
1. GIVEN [initial context/state]
   WHEN [action/event occurs]
   THEN [expected outcome]
   AND [additional outcome if needed]

Example:
1. GIVEN a user is on the venue search page
   WHEN they enter "live music downtown tonight"
   THEN results show venues with live music events
   AND venues are sorted by distance from downtown
   AND only tonight's events are displayed

## Test Coverage Matrix
| AC ID | Acceptance Test | Supporting Unit Tests | Status |
|-------|----------------|----------------------|--------|
| AC1   | test_AC1_*.py  | - test_venue_search.py:test_parse_query | ✅ |
|       |                | - test_ranking.py:test_relevance_score   | ✅ |

## Technical Notes
- Required unit test coverage: 80%
- Required acceptance test coverage: 100% of ACs
- Test annotations required for traceability
- Automated test report generation in CI/CD

## Tasks
1. [ ] Write acceptance tests (100% AC coverage)
2. [ ] Implement feature with unit tests
3. [ ] Update test coverage documentation
4. [ ] Verify all AC tests passing

## Definition of Done
1. All acceptance criteria met and verified
2. Tests written and passing (unit, integration, acceptance)
3. Code reviewed and approved
4. Documentation updated
5. Performance requirements met
6. Security requirements met
7. Accessibility requirements met
8. Test coverage meets thresholds
   - Unit tests: 80% coverage
   - Acceptance tests: 100% of ACs
9. Test documentation updated
10. CI/CD pipeline passing
```

## Testing Standards

### 1. Test Organization
- `tests/acceptance/`: End-to-end tests mapped to ACs
- `tests/unit/`: Component-level tests
- `tests/integration/`: Service integration tests
- `tests/performance/`: Performance benchmarks

### 2. Test Documentation
```python
# Example test annotation format
def test_function():
    """Test description
    AC Reference: US-[Area][Number]-AC[Number]
    Coverage: [list of acceptance criteria covered]
    Dependencies: [list of required components/services]
    """
```

### 3. Automated Test Reporting
Required CI/CD steps:
1. Run unit tests & coverage
2. Run acceptance tests
3. Generate test-to-AC mapping report
4. Update documentation
5. Fail build if coverage thresholds not met

### 4. Git Integration
Branch naming:
- Feature: `feature/US-[Area][Number]-[short-description]`
- Test: `test/US-[Area][Number]-[test-type]`

Commit messages:
```
test(US-[Area][Number]): Add tests for AC[Number]
- Added acceptance test for natural language search
- Added supporting unit tests for query parsing
- Updated test coverage documentation
```

